#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:314
msgid ""
"Taken together, all these module options allow you to precisely customize "
"the driver behavior and test your application with all sorts of "
"permutations. It is also very suitable to emulate hardware that is not yet "
"available, e.g. when developing software for a new upcoming device."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:321
msgid "Video Capture"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:323
msgid ""
"This is probably the most frequently used feature. The video capture device "
"can be configured by using the module options num_inputs, input_types and "
"ccs_cap_mode (see \"Configuring the driver\" for more detailed information), "
"but by default four inputs are configured: a webcam, a TV tuner, an S-Video "
"and an HDMI input, one input for each input type. Those are described in "
"more detail below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:330
msgid ""
"Special attention has been given to the rate at which new frames become "
"available. The jitter will be around 1 jiffy (that depends on the HZ "
"configuration of your kernel, so usually 1/100, 1/250 or 1/1000 of a "
"second), but the long-term behavior is exactly following the framerate. So a "
"framerate of 59.94 Hz is really different from 60 Hz. If the framerate "
"exceeds your kernel's HZ value, then you will get dropped frames, but the "
"frame/field sequence counting will keep track of that so the sequence count "
"will skip whenever frames are dropped."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:341
msgid "Webcam Input"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:343
msgid ""
"The webcam input supports three framesizes: 320x180, 640x360 and 1280x720. "
"It supports frames per second settings of 10, 15, 25, 30, 50 and 60 fps. "
"Which ones are available depends on the chosen framesize: the larger the "
"framesize, the lower the maximum frames per second."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:348
msgid ""
"The initially selected colorspace when you switch to the webcam input will "
"be sRGB."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:353
msgid "TV and S-Video Inputs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:355
msgid ""
"The only difference between the TV and S-Video input is that the TV has a "
"tuner. Otherwise they behave identically."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:358
msgid ""
"These inputs support audio inputs as well: one TV and one Line-In. They both "
"support all TV standards. If the standard is queried, then the Vivid "
"controls 'Standard Signal Mode' and 'Standard' determine what the result "
"will be."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:363
msgid ""
"These inputs support all combinations of the field setting. Special care has "
"been taken to faithfully reproduce how fields are handled for the different "
"TV standards. This is particularly noticeable when generating a horizontally "
"moving image so the temporal effect of using interlaced formats becomes "
"clearly visible. For 50 Hz standards the top field is the oldest and the "
"bottom field is the newest in time. For 60 Hz standards that is reversed: "
"the bottom field is the oldest and the top field is the newest in time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:371
msgid ""
"When you start capturing in V4L2_FIELD_ALTERNATE mode the first buffer will "
"contain the top field for 50 Hz standards and the bottom field for 60 Hz "
"standards. This is what capture hardware does as well."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:375
msgid ""
"Finally, for PAL/SECAM standards the first half of the top line contains "
"noise. This simulates the Wide Screen Signal that is commonly placed there."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:378
#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:462
msgid ""
"The initially selected colorspace when you switch to the TV or S-Video input "
"will be SMPTE-170M."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:381
msgid ""
"The pixel aspect ratio will depend on the TV standard. The video aspect "
"ratio can be selected through the 'Standard Aspect Ratio' Vivid control. "
"Choices are '4x3', '16x9' which will give letterboxed widescreen video and "
"'16x9 Anamorphic' which will give full screen squashed anamorphic widescreen "
"video that will need to be scaled accordingly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:387
msgid ""
"The TV 'tuner' supports a frequency range of 44-958 MHz. Channels are "
"available every 6 MHz, starting from 49.25 MHz. For each channel the "
"generated image will be in color for the +/- 0.25 MHz around it, and in "
"grayscale for +/- 1 MHz around the channel. Beyond that it is just noise. "
"The VIDIOC_G_TUNER ioctl will return 100% signal strength for +/- 0.25 MHz "
"and 50% for +/- 1 MHz. It will also return correct afc values to show "
"whether the frequency is too low or too high."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:395
msgid ""
"The audio subchannels that are returned are MONO for the +/- 1 MHz range "
"around a valid channel frequency. When the frequency is within +/- 0.25 MHz "
"of the channel it will return either MONO, STEREO, either MONO | SAP (for "
"NTSC) or LANG1 | LANG2 (for others), or STEREO | SAP."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:400
msgid ""
"Which one is returned depends on the chosen channel, each next valid channel "
"will cycle through the possible audio subchannel combinations. This allows "
"you to test the various combinations by just switching channels.."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:404
msgid ""
"Finally, for these inputs the v4l2_timecode struct is filled in the dequeued "
"v4l2_buffer struct."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:409
msgid "HDMI Input"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:411
msgid ""
"The HDMI inputs supports all CEA-861 and DMT timings, both progressive and "
"interlaced, for pixelclock frequencies between 25 and 600 MHz. The field "
"mode for interlaced formats is always V4L2_FIELD_ALTERNATE. For HDMI the "
"field order is always top field first, and when you start capturing an "
"interlaced format you will receive the top field first."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:417
msgid ""
"The initially selected colorspace when you switch to the HDMI input or "
"select an HDMI timing is based on the format resolution: for resolutions "
"less than or equal to 720x576 the colorspace is set to SMPTE-170M, for "
"others it is set to REC-709 (CEA-861 timings) or sRGB (VESA DMT timings)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:422
#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:478
msgid ""
"The pixel aspect ratio will depend on the HDMI timing: for 720x480 is it set "
"as for the NTSC TV standard, for 720x576 it is set as for the PAL TV "
"standard, and for all others a 1:1 pixel aspect ratio is returned."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:426
msgid ""
"The video aspect ratio can be selected through the 'DV Timings Aspect Ratio' "
"Vivid control. Choices are 'Source Width x Height' (just use the same ratio "
"as the chosen format), '4x3' or '16x9', either of which can result in "
"pillarboxed or letterboxed video."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:431
msgid ""
"For HDMI inputs it is possible to set the EDID. By default a simple EDID is "
"provided. You can only set the EDID for HDMI inputs. Internally, however, "
"the EDID is shared between all HDMI inputs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:435
msgid ""
"No interpretation is done of the EDID data with the exception of the "
"physical address. See the CEC section for more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:438
msgid ""
"There is a maximum of 15 HDMI inputs (if there are more, then they will be "
"reduced to 15) since that's the limitation of the EDID physical address."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:443
msgid "Video Output"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:445
msgid ""
"The video output device can be configured by using the module options "
"num_outputs, output_types and ccs_out_mode (see \"Configuring the driver\" "
"for more detailed information), but by default two outputs are configured: "
"an S-Video and an HDMI input, one output for each output type. Those are "
"described in more detail below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:451
msgid "Like with video capture the framerate is also exact in the long term."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:455
msgid "S-Video Output"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:457
msgid ""
"This output supports audio outputs as well: \"Line-Out 1\" and \"Line-Out "
"2\". The S-Video output supports all TV standards."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:460
msgid "This output supports all combinations of the field setting."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:467
msgid "HDMI Output"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:469
msgid ""
"The HDMI output supports all CEA-861 and DMT timings, both progressive and "
"interlaced, for pixelclock frequencies between 25 and 600 MHz. The field "
"mode for interlaced formats is always V4L2_FIELD_ALTERNATE."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:473
msgid ""
"The initially selected colorspace when you switch to the HDMI output or "
"select an HDMI timing is based on the format resolution: for resolutions "
"less than or equal to 720x576 the colorspace is set to SMPTE-170M, for "
"others it is set to REC-709 (CEA-861 timings) or sRGB (VESA DMT timings)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:482
msgid ""
"An HDMI output has a valid EDID which can be obtained through VIDIOC_G_EDID."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:484
msgid ""
"There is a maximum of 15 HDMI outputs (if there are more, then they will be "
"reduced to 15) since that's the limitation of the EDID physical address. See "
"also the CEC section for more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:489
msgid "VBI Capture"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:491
msgid ""
"There are three types of VBI capture devices: those that only support raw "
"(undecoded) VBI, those that only support sliced (decoded) VBI and those that "
"support both. This is determined by the node_types module option. In all "
"cases the driver will generate valid VBI data: for 60 Hz standards it will "
"generate Closed Caption and XDS data. The closed caption stream will "
"alternate between \"Hello world!\" and \"Closed captions test\" every "
"second. The XDS stream will give the current time once a minute. For 50 Hz "
"standards it will generate the Wide Screen Signal which is based on the "
"actual Video Aspect Ratio control setting and teletext pages 100-159, one "
"page per frame."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:501
msgid ""
"The VBI device will only work for the S-Video and TV inputs, it will give "
"back an error if the current input is a webcam or HDMI."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:506
msgid "VBI Output"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:508
msgid ""
"There are three types of VBI output devices: those that only support raw "
"(undecoded) VBI, those that only support sliced (decoded) VBI and those that "
"support both. This is determined by the node_types module option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:512
msgid ""
"The sliced VBI output supports the Wide Screen Signal and the teletext "
"signal for 50 Hz standards and Closed Captioning + XDS for 60 Hz standards."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:515
msgid ""
"The VBI device will only work for the S-Video output, it will give back an "
"error if the current output is HDMI."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:520
msgid "Radio Receiver"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:522
msgid ""
"The radio receiver emulates an FM/AM/SW receiver. The FM band also supports "
"RDS. The frequency ranges are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:525
#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:561
msgid "FM: 64 MHz - 108 MHz"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:526
#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:562
msgid "AM: 520 kHz - 1710 kHz"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:527
#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:563
msgid "SW: 2300 kHz - 26.1 MHz"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:529
msgid ""
"Valid channels are emulated every 1 MHz for FM and every 100 kHz for AM and "
"SW. The signal strength decreases the further the frequency is from the "
"valid frequency until it becomes 0% at +/- 50 kHz (FM) or 5 kHz (AM/SW) from "
"the ideal frequency. The initial frequency when the driver is loaded is set "
"to 95 MHz."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:535
msgid ""
"The FM receiver supports RDS as well, both using 'Block I/O' and 'Controls' "
"modes. In the 'Controls' mode the RDS information is stored in read-only "
"controls. These controls are updated every time the frequency is changed, or "
"when the tuner status is requested. The Block I/O method uses the read() "
"interface to pass the RDS blocks on to the application for decoding."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:541
msgid ""
"The RDS signal is 'detected' for +/- 12.5 kHz around the channel frequency, "
"and the further the frequency is away from the valid frequency the more RDS "
"errors are randomly introduced into the block I/O stream, up to 50% of all "
"blocks if you are +/- 12.5 kHz from the channel frequency. All four errors "
"can occur in equal proportions: blocks marked 'CORRECTED', blocks marked "
"'ERROR', blocks marked 'INVALID' and dropped blocks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:548
msgid ""
"The generated RDS stream contains all the standard fields contained in a 0B "
"group, and also radio text and the current time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:551
msgid ""
"The receiver supports HW frequency seek, either in Bounded mode, Wrap Around "
"mode or both, which is configurable with the \"Radio HW Seek Mode\" control."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:556
msgid "Radio Transmitter"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:558
msgid ""
"The radio transmitter emulates an FM/AM/SW transmitter. The FM band also "
"supports RDS. The frequency ranges are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:565
msgid "The initial frequency when the driver is loaded is 95.5 MHz."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:567
msgid ""
"The FM transmitter supports RDS as well, both using 'Block I/O' and "
"'Controls' modes. In the 'Controls' mode the transmitted RDS information is "
"configured using controls, and in 'Block I/O' mode the blocks are passed to "
"the driver using write()."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:574
msgid "Software Defined Radio Receiver"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:576
msgid "The SDR receiver has three frequency bands for the ADC tuner:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:578
msgid "300 kHz"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:579
msgid "900 kHz - 2800 kHz"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:580
msgid "3200 kHz"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:582
msgid "The RF tuner supports 50 MHz - 2000 MHz."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:584
msgid ""
"The generated data contains the In-phase and Quadrature components of a 1 "
"kHz tone that has an amplitude of sqrt(2)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:589
msgid "Metadata Capture"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:591
msgid ""
"The Metadata capture generates UVC format metadata. The PTS and SCR are "
"transmitted based on the values set in vivid controls."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:594
msgid ""
"The Metadata device will only work for the Webcam input, it will give back "
"an error for all other inputs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:599
msgid "Metadata Output"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:601
msgid ""
"The Metadata output can be used to set brightness, contrast, saturation and "
"hue."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:603
msgid ""
"The Metadata device will only work for the Webcam output, it will give back "
"an error for all other outputs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:608
msgid "Touch Capture"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:610
msgid ""
"The Touch capture generates touch patterns simulating single tap, double "
"tap, triple tap, move from left to right, zoom in, zoom out, palm press "
"(simulating a large area being pressed on a touchpad), and simulating 16 "
"simultaneous touch points."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:616
msgid "Controls"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:618
msgid ""
"Different devices support different controls. The sections below will "
"describe each control and which devices support them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:623
msgid "User Controls - Test Controls"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:625
msgid ""
"The Button, Boolean, Integer 32 Bits, Integer 64 Bits, Menu, String, Bitmask "
"and Integer Menu are controls that represent all possible control types. The "
"Menu control and the Integer Menu control both have 'holes' in their menu "
"list, meaning that one or more menu items return EINVAL when "
"VIDIOC_QUERYMENU is called. Both menu controls also have a non-zero minimum "
"control value.  These features allow you to check if your application can "
"handle such things correctly. These controls are supported for every device "
"type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:635
msgid "User Controls - Video Capture"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:637
msgid "The following controls are specific to video capture."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:639
msgid ""
"The Brightness, Contrast, Saturation and Hue controls actually work and are "
"standard. There is one special feature with the Brightness control: each "
"video input has its own brightness value, so changing input will restore the "
"brightness for that input. In addition, each video input uses a different "
"brightness range (minimum and maximum control values). Switching inputs will "
"cause a control event to be sent with the V4L2_EVENT_CTRL_CH_RANGE flag set. "
"This allows you to test controls that can change their range."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:647
msgid ""
"The 'Gain, Automatic' and Gain controls can be used to test volatile "
"controls: if 'Gain, Automatic' is set, then the Gain control is volatile and "
"changes constantly. If 'Gain, Automatic' is cleared, then the Gain control "
"is a normal control."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:652
msgid ""
"The 'Horizontal Flip' and 'Vertical Flip' controls can be used to flip the "
"image. These combine with the 'Sensor Flipped Horizontally/Vertically' Vivid "
"controls."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:656
msgid ""
"The 'Alpha Component' control can be used to set the alpha component for "
"formats containing an alpha channel."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:661
msgid "User Controls - Audio"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:663
msgid ""
"The following controls are specific to video capture and output and radio "
"receivers and transmitters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:666
msgid ""
"The 'Volume' and 'Mute' audio controls are typical for such devices to "
"control the volume and mute the audio. They don't actually do anything in "
"the vivid driver."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:672
msgid "Vivid Controls"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:674
msgid ""
"These vivid custom controls control the image generation, error injection, "
"etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:678
msgid "Test Pattern Controls"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:680
msgid "The Test Pattern Controls are all specific to video capture."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:682
msgid "Test Pattern:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:684
msgid ""
"selects which test pattern to use. Use the CSC Colorbar for testing "
"colorspace conversions: the colors used in that test pattern map to valid "
"colors in all colorspaces. The colorspace conversion is disabled for the "
"other test patterns."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:689
msgid "OSD Text Mode:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:691
msgid ""
"selects whether the text superimposed on the test pattern should be shown, "
"and if so, whether only counters should be displayed or the full text."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:695
msgid "Horizontal Movement:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:697
msgid ""
"selects whether the test pattern should move to the left or right and at "
"what speed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:700
msgid "Vertical Movement:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:702
msgid "does the same for the vertical direction."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:704
msgid "Show Border:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:706
msgid ""
"show a two-pixel wide border at the edge of the actual image, excluding "
"letter or pillarboxing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:709
msgid "Show Square:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:711
msgid ""
"show a square in the middle of the image. If the image is displayed with the "
"correct pixel and image aspect ratio corrections, then the width and height "
"of the square on the monitor should be the same."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:716
msgid "Insert SAV Code in Image:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:718
msgid ""
"adds a SAV (Start of Active Video) code to the image. This can be used to "
"check if such codes in the image are inadvertently interpreted instead of "
"being ignored."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:722
msgid "Insert EAV Code in Image:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:724
msgid "does the same for the EAV (End of Active Video) code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:726
msgid "Insert Video Guard Band"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:728
msgid ""
"adds 4 columns of pixels with the HDMI Video Guard Band code at the left "
"hand side of the image. This only works with 3 or 4 byte RGB pixel formats. "
"The RGB pixel value 0xab/0x55/0xab turns out to be equivalent to the HDMI "
"Video Guard Band code that precedes each active video line (see section "
"5.2.2.1 in the HDMI 1.3 Specification). To test if a video receiver has "
"correct HDMI Video Guard Band processing, enable this control and then move "
"the image to the left hand side of the screen. That will result in video "
"lines that start with multiple pixels that have the same value as the Video "
"Guard Band that precedes them. Receivers that will just keep skipping Video "
"Guard Band values will now fail and either loose sync or these video lines "
"will shift."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:742
msgid "Capture Feature Selection Controls"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:744
msgid "These controls are all specific to video capture."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:746
msgid "Sensor Flipped Horizontally:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:748
msgid ""
"the image is flipped horizontally and the V4L2_IN_ST_HFLIP input status flag "
"is set. This emulates the case where a sensor is for example mounted upside "
"down."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:752
msgid "Sensor Flipped Vertically:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:754
msgid ""
"the image is flipped vertically and the V4L2_IN_ST_VFLIP input status flag "
"is set. This emulates the case where a sensor is for example mounted upside "
"down."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:758
msgid "Standard Aspect Ratio:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:760
msgid ""
"selects if the image aspect ratio as used for the TV or S-Video input should "
"be 4x3, 16x9 or anamorphic widescreen. This may introduce letterboxing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:764
msgid "DV Timings Aspect Ratio:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:766
msgid ""
"selects if the image aspect ratio as used for the HDMI input should be the "
"same as the source width and height ratio, or if it should be 4x3 or 16x9. "
"This may introduce letter or pillarboxing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:770
msgid "Timestamp Source:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:772
msgid "selects when the timestamp for each buffer is taken."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:774
msgid "Colorspace:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:776
msgid ""
"selects which colorspace should be used when generating the image. This only "
"applies if the CSC Colorbar test pattern is selected, otherwise the test "
"pattern will go through unconverted. This behavior is also what you want, "
"since a 75% Colorbar should really have 75% signal intensity and should not "
"be affected by colorspace conversions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:783
msgid ""
"Changing the colorspace will result in the V4L2_EVENT_SOURCE_CHANGE to be "
"sent since it emulates a detected colorspace change."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:786
msgid "Transfer Function:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:788
msgid ""
"selects which colorspace transfer function should be used when generating an "
"image. This only applies if the CSC Colorbar test pattern is selected, "
"otherwise the test pattern will go through unconverted. This behavior is "
"also what you want, since a 75% Colorbar should really have 75% signal "
"intensity and should not be affected by colorspace conversions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:795
msgid ""
"Changing the transfer function will result in the V4L2_EVENT_SOURCE_CHANGE "
"to be sent since it emulates a detected colorspace change."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:798
msgid "Y'CbCr Encoding:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:800
msgid ""
"selects which Y'CbCr encoding should be used when generating a Y'CbCr image. "
"This only applies if the format is set to a Y'CbCr format as opposed to an "
"RGB format."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:804
msgid ""
"Changing the Y'CbCr encoding will result in the V4L2_EVENT_SOURCE_CHANGE to "
"be sent since it emulates a detected colorspace change."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:807
msgid "Quantization:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:809
msgid ""
"selects which quantization should be used for the RGB or Y'CbCr encoding "
"when generating the test pattern."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:812
msgid ""
"Changing the quantization will result in the V4L2_EVENT_SOURCE_CHANGE to be "
"sent since it emulates a detected colorspace change."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:815
msgid "Limited RGB Range (16-235):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:817
msgid ""
"selects if the RGB range of the HDMI source should be limited or full range. "
"This combines with the Digital Video 'Rx RGB Quantization Range' control and "
"can be used to test what happens if a source provides you with the wrong "
"quantization range information. See the description of that control for more "
"details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:823
msgid "Apply Alpha To Red Only:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:825
msgid ""
"apply the alpha channel as set by the 'Alpha Component' user control to the "
"red color of the test pattern only."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:828
msgid "Enable Capture Cropping:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:830
msgid ""
"enables crop support. This control is only present if the ccs_cap_mode "
"module option is set to the default value of -1 and if the no_error_inj "
"module option is set to 0 (the default)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:834
msgid "Enable Capture Composing:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:836
msgid ""
"enables composing support. This control is only present if the ccs_cap_mode "
"module option is set to the default value of -1 and if the no_error_inj "
"module option is set to 0 (the default)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:840
msgid "Enable Capture Scaler:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:842
msgid ""
"enables support for a scaler (maximum 4 times upscaling and downscaling). "
"This control is only present if the ccs_cap_mode module option is set to the "
"default value of -1 and if the no_error_inj module option is set to 0 (the "
"default)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:847
msgid "Maximum EDID Blocks:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:849
msgid ""
"determines how many EDID blocks the driver supports. Note that the vivid "
"driver does not actually interpret new EDID data, it just stores it. It "
"allows for up to 256 EDID blocks which is the maximum supported by the "
"standard."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:854
msgid "Fill Percentage of Frame:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:856
msgid ""
"can be used to draw only the top X percent of the image. Since each frame "
"has to be drawn by the driver, this demands a lot of the CPU. For large "
"resolutions this becomes problematic. By drawing only part of the image this "
"CPU load can be reduced."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:864
msgid "Output Feature Selection Controls"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:866
msgid "These controls are all specific to video output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:868
msgid "Enable Output Cropping:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:870
msgid ""
"enables crop support. This control is only present if the ccs_out_mode "
"module option is set to the default value of -1 and if the no_error_inj "
"module option is set to 0 (the default)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:874
msgid "Enable Output Composing:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:876
msgid ""
"enables composing support. This control is only present if the ccs_out_mode "
"module option is set to the default value of -1 and if the no_error_inj "
"module option is set to 0 (the default)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:880
msgid "Enable Output Scaler:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:882
msgid ""
"enables support for a scaler (maximum 4 times upscaling and downscaling). "
"This control is only present if the ccs_out_mode module option is set to the "
"default value of -1 and if the no_error_inj module option is set to 0 (the "
"default)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:889
msgid "Error Injection Controls"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:891
msgid "The following two controls are only valid for video and vbi capture."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:893
msgid "Standard Signal Mode:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:895
msgid "selects the behavior of VIDIOC_QUERYSTD: what should it return?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:897
#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:917
msgid ""
"Changing this control will result in the V4L2_EVENT_SOURCE_CHANGE to be sent "
"since it emulates a changed input condition (e.g. a cable was plugged in or "
"out)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:901
msgid "Standard:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:903
msgid ""
"selects the standard that VIDIOC_QUERYSTD should return if the previous "
"control is set to \"Selected Standard\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/media/vivid.rst:906
msgid ""
